@node Flex matching
@section Flex matching

@findex orderless-extras-flex-dispatcher
The function @code{orderless-extras-flex-dispatcher} activates @code{orderless-flex} matching for any component that ends with a tilde (@samp{~}). Flex matching allows characters to appear in order but not necessarily adjacent, which is useful when you remember the overall shape of a name but not its exact spelling.

For example, in the query @samp{file sme~ na}, the component @samp{sme~} would flexibly match candidates containing @samp{s}, @samp{m}, and @samp{e} in that order (such as ``some''), while @samp{file} and @samp{na} would use the default matching style.

@node Initialism
@section Initialism

@findex orderless-extras-initialism-dispatcher
The function @code{orderless-extras-initialism-dispatcher} activates @code{orderless-initialism} matching for any component that ends with a comma (@samp{,}). Initialism matching treats each character in the component as the first letter of a word, which is particularly effective for long hyphenated Emacs symbol names.

For example, @samp{ffap,} would match @code{find-file-at-point} because @samp{f}, @samp{f}, @samp{a}, and @samp{p} are the initials of each word.

@node Prefixes
@section Prefixes

@findex orderless-extras-prefixes-dispatcher
The function @code{orderless-extras-prefixes-dispatcher} activates @code{orderless-prefixes} matching for any component that ends with a semicolon (@samp{;}). Prefix matching requires each character group (separated by word boundaries) in the component to appear at the beginning of corresponding words in the candidate.

For example, @samp{or-ex;} would match @samp{orderless-extras} because @samp{or} is a prefix of @samp{orderless} and @samp{ex} is a prefix of @samp{extras}. It would not match a candidate where @samp{ex} appeared in the middle of a word.

@node Exclusion
@section Exclusion

@findex orderless-extras-exclusion-dispatcher
The function @code{orderless-extras-exclusion-dispatcher} activates @code{orderless-without-literal} matching for any component that ends with an exclamation mark (@samp{!}). This excludes any candidate that contains the literal text of the component (minus the trailing @samp{!}).

For example, the query @samp{file tmp!} would match candidates containing @samp{file} but exclude any that also contain @samp{tmp}. This is useful for filtering out noise from a broad search.

